\begin{abstract}
Following the COVID-19 pandemic, consumer behavior
has substantially changed in shopping centers, impacting the performance of
sustainability and management of small enterprises. Numerous local shops
struggle to adjust to new spending habits, decreased spending,
and heightened rivalry from big-box stores. This document
suggests a data-driven system to assist local businesses.
recovery through enhancing client interaction and maximizing
inventory control. The outcomes of the observation
and survey results show that the primary problem is not the absence of
clients, but the absence of organized and easily accessible data.
By combining environmental factors, consumer behavior, and
By consolidating business data into a single system, small businesses can
enhance decision-making, expand sales prospects, and adjust
more successfully in light of the present state of the market.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

In recent years, shopping malls have evolved from being purely commercial spaces into multifunctional environments where people not only shop, but also socialize, eat, work, and spend their leisure time. This transformation became even more evident after the COVID-19 pandemic, which significantly changed consumer behavior and expectations.

Studies such as \cite{ref1,ref2} show that customers now prioritize experience, convenience, and value over traditional purchasing habits. Additionally, many consumers combine online and physical shopping, creating hybrid consumption patterns that challenge traditional retail models \cite{ref3,ref4}. This shift forces businesses to rethink how they interact with customers and how they manage their operations.

Large retail chains have adapted effectively to these changes by adopting data-driven strategies. Among them is the application of
digital platforms, integrated inventory systems, and analytics
that enable them to comprehend client preferences, forecast
demand, and streamline processes [5]. These capacities support
give them a sizable competitive edge and enable them to
react swiftly to shifts in the market.

In contrast, small businesses face important limitations. Many of them rely on manual processes or fragmented sources of information, which reduces their ability to respond to customer needs in real time. As a result, they experience problems such as low sales conversion, inefficient inventory management, and loss of customers to larger competitors \cite{ref6}.

Another important factor is the change in spending behavior. After the pandemic, a considerable percentage of customers reported reducing their expenses. This directly impacts small businesses, which depend heavily on frequent purchases. This situation increases the importance of making accurate and informed decisions.

This creates a gap between customer demand and business supply. While customers are physically present in shopping malls, their needs are not always satisfied due to poor information management. Understanding this gap is essential to improving the performance and sustainability of small businesses.

In this paper, we analyze the behavior of customers and small businesses within a real shopping mall environment. Based on this analysis, we propose a data-driven system that integrates customer behavior, environmental variables, and business data to support decision-making.

\section{Methods and Materials}

To understand the problem, a combination of qualitative and quantitative methods was used. This approach allowed obtaining a more complete and reliable understanding of the system.

Direct observation was used to analyze how customers move within the shopping mall. This method allowed identifying high-traffic areas, peak hours, and patterns of behavior. It also helped detect zones where customer presence does not translate into sales.

Customers and employees were surveyed. Consumers gave details about their purchasing habits, frequency of visits, and preferences. Workers shared information about inventory problems, sales patterns, and operational difficulties. The analysis was enhanced by this blend of viewpoints.

Environmental analysis focused on external variables such as weather conditions, day of the week, and special events. These factors influence customer behavior and introduce variability into the system, making decision-making more complex.

